# deny_terms.txt.example — template for the anonymization blocklist (no real names, safe to publish)
#
# In actual use, copy this to report/deny_terms.txt and add the real personal names,
# organization names, account names, etc., one term per line.
# The real deny_terms.txt is gitignored (never put real names in a public repo).
#
# In the final stage of report generation, the artifacts (text extracted from the docx body,
# PDF metadata) are checked against this list using case-insensitive substring matching.
# A single hit fails the build (fail-safe, since the output is meant to be published).
#
# Format:
#   - Blank lines and lines starting with # are ignored.
#   - Every other line is a "term that must not appear". Leading/trailing whitespace is trimmed.
#
# ---- Environment-derived terms (auto-detectable; replace with real values in actual use) ----
# GitHub account / repository name
YOUR_GITHUB_ACCOUNT
# Local username / home path fragment
YOUR_LOCAL_USERNAME
/Users/YOUR_LOCAL_USERNAME
# Email address fragment
YOUR_EMAIL_LOCALPART
# Cloud storage name / a name specific to the local environment
YOUR_CLOUD_STORAGE_NAME
#
# ---- Categories for humans to fill in (put the actual terms in the real deny_terms.txt) ----
#   - Real personal names (names of practitioners/researchers not to be reflected in the report, etc.)
#   - Names of employers/affiliated organizations (names that could reveal the industry)
#   - Names of related parties or third parties that could aid identification
#   - Hostnames/identifiers of deploy targets or other projects
#   - Any other identifying information that could single out an individual
